Build succeeds. Here's the approach — use the established **`System.IO.Abstractions`** NuGet package instead of hand-rolling a wrapper:

### What changed

`ReportGenerator` now takes `IFileSystem` via primary constructor injection. All `File.*`, `Directory.*`, and `Path.*` calls go through it:

```csharp
public class ReportGenerator(IFileSystem fileSystem)
{
    // fileSystem.File.WriteAllText(...)
    // fileSystem.File.ReadAllText(...)
    // fileSystem.Directory.Exists(...)
}
```

### DI registration (in `Program.cs`)

```csharp
builder.Services.AddSingleton<IFileSystem, FileSystem>();
```

### Testing with `MockFileSystem`

Install the test helpers:
```
dotnet add <TestProject> package System.IO.Abstractions.TestingHelpers
```

Then in your tests:
```csharp
var mockFs = new MockFileSystem();
var generator = new ReportGenerator(mockFs);

generator.GenerateReport("Sales");

// Assert against the in-memory file system
var files = mockFs.Directory.GetFiles("/tmp/reports");
Assert.Single(files);
```

No real disk I/O, fully deterministic, and `System.IO.Abstractions` covers the entire `System.IO` surface so you won't need to extend it.
